Core Problem
You're relying on a cookie-based anonymous ID, which breaks when:

Safari/Firefox ITP caps cookie lifetimes (often 7 days or even 24hrs for JS-set cookies)
Users clear cookies/storage manually or via browser settings


Fix: Use a Persistence Hierarchy
Layer multiple storage mechanisms so if one breaks, you fall back to the next.
Layer 1 — Server-side cookie (most durable)
Set the user ID as an HttpOnly cookie from your server, not via JavaScript. ITP treats server-set cookies much more leniently (up to 1 year in many cases vs. 7 days for JS cookies).



http
Set-Cookie: uid=abc123; Max-Age=31536000; Path=/; Secure; HttpOnly; SameSite=LaxThis is the single biggest win — do this first.

Layer 2 — localStorage as a fallback sync
Store the ID in localStorage alongside the cookie. On page load, reconcile them:



javascript
function getOrCreateUserId() {
  // 1. Trust server cookie first (read via a /me endpoint or injected into page)
  const serverUid = window.__SERVER_UID; // injected by your server
  if (serverUid) {
    localStorage.setItem('uid', serverUid);
    return serverUid;
  }

  // 2. Fall back to localStorage
  let uid = localStorage.getItem('uid');
  if (uid) return uid;

  // 3. Generate new ID as last resort
  uid = crypto.randomUUID();
  localStorage.setItem('uid', uid);
  return uid;
}

Layer 3 — Authenticated ID (best long-term solution)
If your product has any login/account system, tie tracking to the authenticated user ID. This survives cookie clears, device switches, and browser restrictions entirely. Even a lightweight "remember me" email flow helps enormously.
